theorem perfect_pseudoperfect (h : Perfect n) : Pseudoperfect n := 
  ⟨h.2, _, mem_powerset_self _, h.1⟩
```
Here `h.1` and `h.2` automatically pull out the two parts of the `and` statement defining `Pseudoperfect n`. The underscores work because Lean is capable of figuring out what to put, so you don't need to bother to write it.

I wanted to demonstrate that a deficient number could never be abundant or perfect. I wanted to show that exclusivity for the other factorisation properties as well.

The thing we'd like to have here is "for a natural number n, exactly one of the following is true: n=0, n is deficient, n is abundant, n is perfect". Like David I'm not convinced that these lemmas are the right way to say this, but on the other hand it would be nice to be able to express this idea in a useful way.
Would an xor work?
I think that what we have right now will do.

`k` never gets used. Moreover, for most of the lemmas, `n` can be inferred from the other arguments so it doesn't need to be given explicitly; that is, you should do `variable {n : ℕ}` and then override it with `(n : ℕ)` in individual declarations where it isn't inferrable. (Note that in theorems whose conclusion is an "iff" statement, it's usual to have variables implicit if they can be inferred from both sides of the "iff", which is the case for your lemma `not_pseudoperfect_iff_forall` for example.)

golfing suggestion:

theorem prime_not_pseudoperfect (h : Nat.Prime n) : ¬ Nat.Pseudoperfect n := by
  rw [not_pseudoperfect_iff_forall, 
    show powerset (properDivisors n) = {∅, {1}} by rw [Prime.properDivisors h]; rfl]
  refine Or.inr (fun s hs ↦ ?_)
  fin_cases hs <;>
  simp only [sum_empty, sum_singleton] <;>
  linarith [Prime.one_lt h]
```
